## Summary

At the moment most of the classes used for runtime compilation are internal and it is nearly impossible to extend it without copying many classes to your own project. I would like to adapt some of them to make it easy to extend.

## Motivation and goals

I am creating a system which is able to dynamically load and unload plugins containing MVC controller/views and Razor components. This works fine with a simple custom view-compiler if you do not use runtime compilation. Especially for development, but also for "UI/text quick-fixes" on live systems it would be great to be able to add/change `*.cshtml` files of such plugins and get them runtime-compiled.  

## In scope

With the current `RuntimeViewCompiler` you cannot do the following:

- add dynamically loaded pre-compiled views
- add a file-path to watch for changed views after the compiler is initialized
- unload and reload the same model-types

## Out of scope

The actual logic to solve the two points from above should not be part of this. Just the possibility to add such functionality without the need to copy/change framework classes.

## Risks / unknowns

Opening up some of the classes could create backwards-compatibility issues if such classes are planned to be changed in the future. My proposal for the changes are based on my implementation and maybe I did miss some points to make this useful for everyone or other cases.

## Examples

The following class is an example-implementation of an extended `RuntimeViewCompiler` which is able to solve point 1) & 3) from above. For this it adds pre-compiled views to the precompiled views list with a custom cancelation token to cancel them when the views are unloaded and uses a custom load-context to load the runtime-compiled views to be able to unload them with the plugin:

```
public class PluginViewCompiler : RuntimeViewCompiler
{
	public static PluginViewCompiler Instance { get; private set; }

	private readonly ConcurrentDictionary<AssemblyLoadContext, List<string>> loadedViews = new();
	private readonly ConcurrentDictionary<string, CancellationTokenSource> viewsTokenSources = new();

	public PluginViewCompiler(IFileProvider fileProvider, RazorProjectEngine projectEngine, CSharpCompiler csharpCompiler, IList<CompiledViewDescriptor> precompiledViews, ILogger logger)
		: base(fileProvider, projectEngine, csharpCompiler, precompiledViews, logger)
	{
		Instance = this;
	}

	public void LoadCompiledViews(AssemblyLoadContext context, IRazorCompiledItemProvider itemProvider)
	{
		var cancellationTokenSource = new CancellationTokenSource();
		viewsTokenSources.AddOrUpdate(context.Name, _ => cancellationTokenSource, (_, i) =>
			{
				cancellationTokenSource = i;
				return i;
			});

		foreach (var compiledItem in itemProvider.CompiledItems)
		{
			var compiledView = new CompiledViewDescriptor(compiledItem);
			if (PrecompiledViews.ContainsKey(compiledView.RelativePath))
				continue;

			compiledView.ExpirationTokens = new List<IChangeToken>() {new CancellationChangeToken(cancellationTokenSource.Token)};
			PrecompiledViews.Add(compiledView.RelativePath, compiledView);
		}
	}

	public void UnloadViews(AssemblyLoadContext context)
	{
		var compiledViews = PrecompiledViews.Where(kvp => context.Assemblies.Contains(kvp.Value.Type.Assembly)).ToList();
		foreach (var entry in compiledViews)
			PrecompiledViews.Remove(entry.Key);

		if (viewsTokenSources.TryRemove(context.Name, out var contextSource))
			contextSource.Cancel();

		if (!loadedViews.TryRemove(context, out var views))
			return;

		views.ForEach(i =>
			{
				if (viewsTokenSources.TryRemove(i, out var source))
					source.Cancel();
			});
	}

	protected override IList<IChangeToken> GetExpirationTokens(CompiledViewDescriptor precompiledView)
	{
		var expirationTokens = base.GetExpirationTokens(precompiledView);

		foreach (var token in precompiledView.ExpirationTokens)
			expirationTokens.Add(token);

		return expirationTokens;
	}

	protected override void GetChangeTokensFromImports(IList<IChangeToken> expirationTokens, RazorProjectItem projectItem)
	{
		base.GetChangeTokensFromImports(expirationTokens, projectItem);

		var tokenSource = new CancellationTokenSource();
		expirationTokens.Add(new CancellationChangeToken(tokenSource.Token));
		viewsTokenSources[projectItem.FilePath] = tokenSource;
	}

	protected override Assembly LoadAssembly(RazorCodeDocument codeDocument, MemoryStream assemblyStream, MemoryStream pdbStream)
	{
		string relativePath = codeDocument.Source.RelativePath;
		var pluginPath = codeDocument.Source.FilePath.Substring(0, codeDocument.Source.FilePath.Length - codeDocument.Source.RelativePath.Length);
		var pluginContext = PluginService.Current.GetContext(pluginPath.Split('\\', '/').Last());
		var assembly = (pluginContext ?? AssemblyLoadContext.Default).LoadFromStream(assemblyStream, pdbStream);
		if (pluginContext != null)
		{
			loadedViews.AddOrUpdate(pluginContext, _ => new List<string>() {relativePath}, (_, l) =>
				{
					if (!l.Contains(relativePath))
						l.Add(relativePath);
					return l;
				});
		}

		return assembly;
	}
}
```
This compiler must be loaded via a custom `IViewCompilerProvider` which is easy to implement.

And the following is an extension of the `RuntimeCompilationFileProvider` class to be able to add new file-paths after the compiler is initialized to solve point 2) by supplying an `IFileProvider` which can be altered:

```
public class PluginFileProvider : RuntimeCompilationFileProvider
{
	public PluginFileProvider(IFileProvider fileProvider, IOptions<MvcRazorRuntimeCompilationOptions options) : base(options)
	{
		FileProvider = fileProvider;
	}

	public override IFileProvider FileProvider { get; }
}
```
This class must be registered with `services.AddSingleton<RuntimeCompilationFileProvider, PluginFileProvider>();` before the runtime compilation is initialized as it is then picked up instead of the base class.

> Thanks for adding this. We're using `ServerOptionsSelectionCallback` and `SslStreamCertificateContext` to enable hosting thousands of domains and selecting the right ssl certificates with Kestrel. Though `X509Certificate2` on Windows does have temporary file creation issues that don't disappear with dispose that we have to deal with.
> 
> I had to spend some time to figure this out and to get it working with HTTP/2. Posting some sample code here for the benefit of others trying to use `ServerOptionsSelectionCallback`, for inclusion in documentation, and if anything with the sample code triggers changes/improvements.
> 
> We needed `ConfigureAlpn` to enable HTTP/2. Maybe this method should be made public in `HttpsConnectionMiddleware` or called internally in `HttpsConnectionMiddleware` for us?
> 
> Also would be great to have access to `ConnectionContext` so we can get the connecting ip, listening port, etc. to make certain decisions at this stage or to abort the connection if we didn't find a matching certificate or for any other reasons. If there is a best practice there on how to drop the connection when a matching certificate is not found, would be glad to hear it. Right now, we just return null as the certificate and let Kestrel drop the connection.
> 
> ```c#
> listenOptions.UseHttps(ServerOptionsSelectionCallback, state: listenOptions.Protocols);
> 
> ValueTask<SslServerAuthenticationOptions> ServerOptionsSelectionCallback(
> 	SslStream stream,
> 	SslClientHelloInfo clientHelloInfo,
> 	object state,
> 	CancellationToken cancellationToken)
> {
> 	var serverOptions = new SslServerAuthenticationOptions
> 	{
> 		EnabledSslProtocols = SslProtocols.Tls12 | SslProtocols.Tls13,
> 		CertificateRevocationCheckMode = X509RevocationMode.NoCheck,
> 		ServerCertificateContext = SslStreamCertificateContext.Create(certificate, intermediateCertificates, offline: true)
> 	};
> 
> 	//ConfigureAlpn / Enable Http2
> 	var httpProtocols = (HttpProtocols)state;
> 	ConfigureAlpn(serverOptions, httpProtocols);
> 
> 	return new ValueTask<SslServerAuthenticationOptions>(serverOptions);
> }
> 
> //Copy of method from:
> //https://github.com/dotnet/aspnetcore/blob/main/src/Servers/Kestrel/Core/src/Middleware/HttpsConnectionMiddleware.cs
> void ConfigureAlpn(SslServerAuthenticationOptions serverOptions, HttpProtocols httpProtocols)
> {
> 	serverOptions.ApplicationProtocols = new List<SslApplicationProtocol>();
> 
> 	// This is order sensitive
> 	if ((httpProtocols & HttpProtocols.Http2) != 0)
> 	{
> 		serverOptions.ApplicationProtocols.Add(SslApplicationProtocol.Http2);
> 		// https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc7540#section-9.2.1
> 		serverOptions.AllowRenegotiation = false;
> 	}
> 
> 	if ((httpProtocols & HttpProtocols.Http1) != 0)
> 	{
> 		serverOptions.ApplicationProtocols.Add(SslApplicationProtocol.Http11);
> 	}
> }
> ```

Thanks @nitinag for reporting this issue in https://github.com/dotnet/aspnetcore/pull/25390#issuecomment-807328841.

I think having a public static `ConfigureAlpn` method like @nitinag suggests is a reasonable approach. It's internal rather than private today so [SniOptionsSelector can call it](https://github.com/dotnet/aspnetcore/blob/ec0841d8d7e0c2e700c52bd4d89e7687d9ed78a1/src/Servers/Kestrel/Core/src/Internal/SniOptionsSelector.cs#L95) which probably should have been a sign it should be made public in the first place.

My only concern is that people still won't know to call it and therefore unintentionally disable HTTP/2 when trying to write custom SNI logic. API docs can help here, but not everyone reads it.

I wonder if instead we should automatically populate `ApplicationProtocols` if its null. The question there becomes what if I want to disable ALPN? Is that important? Could that be done with an empty list instead of a null list?

We shouldn't let perfect be the enemy of the good though. If we cannot autopupulate the ALPN list for whatever reason, we should just expose `ConfigureAlpn`. It shouldn't be necessary for people to copy/paste this code.

